Hello

<!-- @slide
title: Clockwork **Utopia**
sub: (In Mia's brain)
-->

<!-- @slide
img: clockwork/movement.jpg
caption: >
  1920's **Mauthe** Wall Clock
-->

During the pandemic
I got really into a British TV show called
The Repair Shop,
and particularly interested in clock repair.
I wanted something to do with my hands,
and I wanted it to feel _useful_,
and I wanted to understand how clocks _work_.

<!-- @slide
img: clockwork/center-wheel.jpg
caption: >
  Early designs for my clock
-->

And I was excited to find out
the basics are learnable!
And I started working on designs for a clock of my own.

<!-- @slide
img: clockwork/clear-craze.jpg
caption: 90's "clear craze"
-->

My plan is to laser cut and 3d print the parts
using colorful plastic,
aiming for a 90s clear craze aesthetic.

<!-- @slide
pre: A clock "_movement_"
title: In Five Parts…
-->

There's some metaphor here
with a society, or a political movement.

<!-- @slide
title: >
  **Power** Source
sub: Usually a spring (compact) or weight (consistent)
caption: wants to unwind!
-->

The spring or weight is really a battery,
storing the energy that we put in,
and releasing it over time.
If you have a clock that you wind,
you are the power source.

A self-winding watch
just uses a small weight and ratchet
so your arm-movements are constantly winding.

By default, a spring will want to unwind immediately,
releasing all the power at once.

<!-- @slide
title: >
  Gear **Train**
sub: Convert between speed & strength
caption: how the power moves around
-->

The gear train is a series of levers
that convert power between force and distance.
We start with a lot of force concentrated at one end,
in the spring or weight --
and but each smaller gear
will move faster with less force.
At the other end of the gear train,
it takes very little force
to stop the entire thing from moving.

But a full turn of the small gear
might only release a small fraction of our power.
The bigger the ratio,
the longer our clock will run --
but also the bigger weight we'll need
to run it.

but still,
this will spin freely.

<!-- @slide
title: >
  Periodic **Regulator**
sub: A pendulum works pretty well
caption: wants to remain constant!
-->

We also need something
that we can use to keep time.
Since the swing of a pendulum is consistent,
that works pretty well.

But because of friction,
we can't have perpetual motion --
so we'll need to give it more power on occasion.

<!-- @slide
title: >
  **Escapement** Mechanism
sub: What makes something a 'clockwork'
caption: limits the flow of power
-->

The escapement is what connects these two parts.
On either end of the pendulum swing,
the anchor catches the gears
to stop them from moving.
On the return swing,
power is allowed to escape,
some of it pushing the pendulum.

Tick tock,
catch and release.

<!-- @slide
title: >
  Dial & **Hands**
sub: Called the 'motion works'
caption: how we read the time
-->

Finally we need a display.
These are a couple more gears
that do the math we need for understanding.
First converting from the speed of the pendulum
to the speed of the second or minute hand
(which rotates once per hour).
Then again, dividing that speed by 12
to get an hour hand
rotating twice per day.

<!-- @slide
pre: Clockwork **math**
title: Is **Not Reliable**
-->

There is _math_ involved with clockworks --
most of it in gear ratios
and choosing a pendulum length.

But that math doesn't make it _reliable_,
because friction is unpredictable, and it adds up.
Friction in the works will depend on oil and dirt,
Friction in the air will depend on
temperature and humidity,
the materials will expand and contract --
even gravity is different
depending where you are.

<!-- @slide
title: Everything **Adjusts**
-->

So the solution is to make everything _adjustable_.
The math doesn't have to be perfect,
because you can dial it in
to get the result you want.

This is currently where my project stalled.
My measurement is correct based on the math,
but I need to build in an adjustment
because it's not working.

<!-- @slide
pre: The _tinkerer_
title: Relationship to **Time**
-->

I also enjoy the relationship to time
that comes from _tinkering on clocks_.
Every clock repair person I've met
is a _tinkerer_.

They might be working on a clock,
but they are clearly not _on the clock_.
In fact, the clock isn't running.
And I enjoy that.
We repair clocks to pass the time,
not to enforce a schedule.

I think that's different
from how most people relate to clocks.

I used to work as an electrician,
and there was a similar irony involved.
When you're working on a light,
you're always working in the dark.
Working without access to power.

<!-- @slide
pre: 2020…
img: clockwork/Timnit_Gebru.jpg
title: Timnit Gebru
sub: AI Ethicist fired from Google
url: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_parrot
source: >
  On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots: Can Language Models Be Too Big?
-->

Around the same time,
there was a big scandal in tech circles
when Google tried to block publishing of a paper
written primarily by their own AI ethics researchers.
Timnit Gebru write a public letter in response,
asking for more transparency,
and she was fired.

<!-- @slide
title: >
  "Stochastic Parrots"
md: >
  Repeat the _likely text_,
  without "_understanding_" it
-->

Stochastic often means
random in the details,
but predictable at a large scale.
An educated guess.

In this case,
a program that returns a somewhat random,
but statistically likely response to a prompt.

<!-- @slide
pre: Some concerns
title: About the **Approach**
md: |
  - environmental footprint
  - financial costs
  - the inscrutability of large models (a black box!)
  - bias is 'learned' without being 'taught'
  - the inability of LLMs to understand the language they process
  - spread of disinformation
-->

That paper specifically raises concerns
about Large language models,

<!-- @slide
youtube: P7XT4TWLzJw
caption: Timnit Gebru - Eugenics and the Promise of Utopia through AGI
-->

But Timnit was also drawing attention to
the people hyping Large Language Models
as a form of "Artificial Intelligence" --
and specifically "Artificial General Intelligence" --
many of them explicitly drawing on ideas of eugenics,
and other techno-utopian philosophies.

<!-- @slide
pre: Ask them to define
title: Artificial **General** Intelligence
-->

The idea of AGI is that
we'll reach a point where intelligence is _exponential_.
If we can build a machine that is smarter than us,
it will be able to build something even smarter.

Despite scientists arguing
that we don't know what intelligence is,
the only ways we measure it
are biased and based in eugenics,
and we don't have any reason to believe
it can be _increased_ exponentially.

Basically to describe AGI
they have to describe an all-powerful being.

<!-- @slide
url: https://www.techdirt.com/2023/11/30/elon-says-copyright-ai-lawsuits-dont-matter-because-digital-god-will-arrive-before-theyre-decided/
source: Tech Dirt
-->

A digital god
that will either save or destroy humanity.

And yeah,
it's the same guys claiming it might save or destroy humanity.
It doesn't matter which,
as long as we understand they are creating a god.

<!-- @slide
img: clockwork/torment.jpg
fit: contain
-->

They're the same guys
telling us that they are Frankenstein,
or naming their companies like
_Skynet_ after Terminator movies.
They constantly reference science fiction,
with themselves as the bad guys.

<!-- @slide
title: Longtermism
sub: Numbers are bigger when you multiply them
-->

Many of them --
Elon Musk, etc --
believe in some version of _longtermism_.

This is not just the idea
that we should care about the future,
but that _mathematically_
the future is _all that matters_.
The whole philosophy is built on
multiplying small numbers by long time periods.

<!-- @slide
pre: If _people have value_
title: |
  Then **more people** \
  have **more value**
-->

<!-- @slide
pre: There's finite room on Earth…
title: But **Infinite Room** in Space!
-->

<!-- @slide
pre: If we invent _digital people_
title: Then We Need **Less Space**
-->

<!-- @slide
sub: Don't worry about _suffering now_
title: A **Far Future** Utopia
md: |
  All that matters is…
  - Colonizing Mars
  - Increasing birth rates
  - Inventing digital people
-->

<!-- @slide
img: clockwork/trolly.png
fit: contain
-->

They present this as a Trolly problem,
where you have a choice to kill some people now,
but that will potentially save _hundreds of trillions_ of people
in the far future.

And it's purely accidental
when their conclusion is
the only people who matter today
are the people colonizing space
and building AI.

Everything is a math problem,
where anything can be multiplied by a trillion years.
No one asks if maybe all these people tied to the track
represent some more pressing issue
that needs a systemic solution
before it comes down to one person pulling a lever.

<!-- @slide
title: Roko's Basilisk
-->

Given enough time AGI is _inevitable_,
so we should be the ones to build it.
Once there are digital people,
they will far outnumber organic people --
so mathematically _this must already be a simulation_.

If this is already a simulation,
and we've already invented god,
then what's to stop the AI from punishing people
who refuse to invent AI?

<!-- @slide
source: Every Society Invents the Failed Utopia it Deserves
url: https://publicdomainreview.org/essay/every-society-invents-the-failed-utopia-it-deserves/
-->

So these things were on my mind
when I read
_Every Society Invents the Failed Utopia it Deserves_.

